{"title":"After working with a dual-screen portable monitor for a month, Iâ€™m a believer","link":"https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2024/11/after-working-with-a-dual-screen-portable-monitor-for-a-month-im-a-believer/","date":1731589245000,"content":"<p>Having two displays in a single device is a growing trend that appeals to people with limited desk space or who need extra pixels to work with when on the go. But often, dual-screen devices, like laptops, are loaded with trade-offs that detract from the convenience two screens should provide.</p>\n<p>I've tried using dual-screen laptops as my primary display/computing device before. But if I were to buy a dual-screen gadget today, it would be a dual-screen portable monitor. After spending the last month using a dual-screen portable monitor as my main work display, I believe that laptops should leave the dual-display thing to portable monitors. At least for now.</p>\n<h2>Clever design tricks simplify use</h2>\n<figure>\n      <img width=\"1024\" height=\"485\" src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/unified-1024x485.jpg\" alt=\"Dual-screen portable monitor\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/unified-1024x485.jpg 1024w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/unified-640x303.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/unified-768x363.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/unified-1536x727.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/unified-2048x969.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/unified-980x464.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/unified-1440x681.jpg 1440w\" />\n      <figcaption>\n        <div>\n    <div></div>\n    <div>\n      Dual screens let you view more on a screen at once. \n\n              <span>\n          Credit:\n\n          \n          Scharon Harding\n\n                  </span>\n          </div>\n  </div>\n      </figcaption>\n    </figure>\n      <figure>\n      <img width=\"1024\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/top-down-view-hinge-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"Dual-screen portable monitor\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/top-down-view-hinge-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/top-down-view-hinge-640x360.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/top-down-view-hinge-768x432.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/top-down-view-hinge-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/top-down-view-hinge-2048x1152.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/top-down-view-hinge-384x216.jpg 384w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/top-down-view-hinge-1152x648.jpg 1152w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/top-down-view-hinge-980x551.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/top-down-view-hinge-1440x810.jpg 1440w\" />\n      <figcaption>\n        <div>\n    <div></div>\n    <div>\n      A top-down view of the hinge. \n\n              <span>\n          Credit:\n\n          \n          Scharon Harding\n\n                  </span>\n          </div>\n  </div>\n      </figcaption>\n    </figure>\n      <figure>\n      <img width=\"1024\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/open-profile-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"Dual-screen portable monitor\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/open-profile-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/open-profile-640x360.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/open-profile-768x432.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/open-profile-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/open-profile-2048x1152.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/open-profile-384x216.jpg 384w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/open-profile-1152x648.jpg 1152w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/open-profile-980x551.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/open-profile-1440x810.jpg 1440w\" />\n      <figcaption>\n        <div>\n    <div></div>\n    <div>\n      A profile view of the thin display. \n\n              <span>\n          Credit:\n\n          \n          Scharon Harding\n\n                  </span>\n          </div>\n  </div>\n      </figcaption>\n    </figure>\n      <figure>\n      <img width=\"1024\" height=\"485\" src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/side-closed-1024x485.jpg\" alt=\"Dual-screen portable monitor\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/side-closed-1024x485.jpg 1024w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/side-closed-640x303.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/side-closed-768x364.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/side-closed-1536x727.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/side-closed-2048x969.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/side-closed-980x464.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/side-closed-1440x682.jpg 1440w\" />\n      <figcaption>\n        <div>\n    <div></div>\n    <div>\n      The monitor shut, with the hinge on the left side.\n\n              <span>\n          Credit:\n\n          \n          Scharon Harding\n\n                  </span>\n          </div>\n  </div>\n      </figcaption>\n    </figure>\n      <figure>\n      <img width=\"1024\" height=\"708\" src=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/backside-1024x708.jpg\" alt=\"Dual-screen portable monitor\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/backside-1024x708.jpg 1024w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/backside-640x442.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/backside-768x531.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/backside-1536x1062.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/backside-2048x1416.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/backside-980x677.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/backside-1440x995.jpg 1440w\" />\n      <figcaption>\n        <div>\n    <div></div>\n    <div>\n      The monitor's backside when open. \n\n              <span>\n          Credit:\n\n          \n          Scharon Harding\n\n                  </span>\n          </div>\n  </div>\n      </figcaption>\n    </figure>\n  \n<p>These days, several companies offer dual-screen monitors, including some Chinese brands you may not have heard of on Amazon and Acer. The monitor I tested is from JSAUX, a Shenzhen-headquartered company that has been around for eight years and has made a name for itself <a href=\"https://www.theverge.com/23769329/jsaux-valve-steam-deck-pc-gaming-accessories-china-interview-hands-on-testing\">selling Steam Deck accessories</a>.</p><p><a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2024/11/after-working-with-a-dual-screen-portable-monitor-for-a-month-im-a-believer/\">Read full article</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2024/11/after-working-with-a-dual-screen-portable-monitor-for-a-month-im-a-believer/#comments\">Comments</a></p>","author":"Scharon Harding","siteTitle":"Ars Technica","siteHash":"5b0ddf6e8923e49262a7894cfd77962733e43fbcc565a103b48373820b310636","entryHash":"885e86d7d1167ae8d74ec4f41c6ef6cfc6835edd466dc7f28c3289280638fcc1","category":"Tech"}